{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 05:39:48.221082", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and approach\n- Verified L3 reachability across OSPF.\n- Validated DNS resolution paths and HTTP access to the load balancer and web backends.\n- Compared DHCP-delivered resolver settings across subnets.\n- Inspected FRR route tables on core, distribution, and server-facing routers.\n\nKey findings\n\n1) Control- and data-plane reachability (healthy)\n- End-to-end ICMP reachability across user subnets, core, distribution, and server VLAN is good (0% loss observed in sampled pings).\n- OSPF adjacencies and routes look correct and stable:\n  - router_core_1, router_dist_1_1, server_access_router all show expected OSPF-learned routes and connected networks in the routing table.\n  - Server farm 10.200.0.0/24 is directly connected on server_access_router and is reachable from hosts.\n\n2) DNS resolution anomaly affecting subnet 10.1.1.0/24\n- Host in 10.1.1.0/24 (host_1_1_1_1):\n  - /etc/resolv.conf = nameserver 8.8.8.8\n  - getent hosts web99.local timed out (>10s).\n  - curl to http://web99.local shows ~5.0 s totals with namelookup/connect at 0, consistent with DNS timeout behavior.\n  - Explicit nslookup against the internal DNS (nslookup web99.local 10.200.0.2) succeeds and returns 10.200.0.7, proving the internal DNS works when queried.\n- Host in 10.2.1.0/24 (host_2_1_1_1):\n  - /etc/resolv.conf = nameserver 10.200.0.2\n  - getent hosts web99.local returns 10.200.0.7 immediately.\n  - curl http://web99.local succeeds with normal lookup (~5–8 ms) and total ~1.0–1.1 s.\n- DHCP server configuration confirms the discrepancy:\n  - dhcpd.conf sets option domain-name-servers 8.8.8.8 for subnet 10.1.1.0/24 only.\n  - All other subnets specify 10.200.0.2.\n- Localization and root cause:\n  - Faulty device: dhcp_server.\n  - Root cause: DHCP misconfiguration for 10.1.1.0/24, handing out a public DNS server (8.8.8.8) instead of the internal DNS (10.200.0.2), causing local name resolution failures from that subnet.\n\n3) Policy compliance issue: back-end web servers are directly accessible from hosts\n- By design, the backend web servers (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6) should not be directly accessible from hosts.\n- Observed behavior:\n  - From hosts, ICMP to web_server_0…web_server_3 succeeds.\n  - HTTP curl to backend IPs from hosts succeeds (starttransfer ~0.22–1.3 s, total ~1.0–2.1 s).\n  - Internal DNS publishes A records for web0.local…web3.local (getent on host_2_1_1_1 resolves them).\n- Localization and root cause:\n  - There appears to be no filtering between user subnets and the server farm; and DNS publishes backend hostnames.\n  - Devices implicated: server_access_router (lack of access control between user networks and backend subnet) and/or dns_server (backend A records exposed to clients).\n  - Root cause: Security/policy misconfiguration allowing direct reachability and discoverability of backend servers.\n\nService component checks (normal)\n- dns_server is listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and responds when queried directly.\n- Load balancer 10.200.0.7 is reachable and responds via HTTP normally from hosts with correct DNS configuration.\n\nImpact summary\n- Users in 10.1.1.0/24 experience failures resolving internal FQDNs (e.g., web99.local), even though network connectivity is fine. Access by IP may still work.\n- Enterprise policy that backend web servers not be directly accessible from hosts is not enforced; users can reach backends by IP and via DNS A records.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 42444, "output_tokens": 3295, "total_tokens": 45739, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 41600}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2368}}}
